# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: representation-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] In mathematics, more specifically in group theory, the **character** of a group representation is a function on the group that associates to each group element the trace of the corresponding matrix.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The character carries the essential information about the representation in a more condensed form.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Georg Frobenius initially developed representation theory of finite groups entirely based on the characters, and without any explicit matrix realization of representations themselves.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] This is possible because a complex representation of a finite group is determined (up to isomorphism) by its character.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The situation with representations over a field of positive characteristic, so-called "modular representations", is more delicate, but Richard Brauer developed a powerful theory of characters in this case as well.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Many deep theorems on the structure of finite groups use characters of modular representations.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Characters of irreducible representations encode many important properties of a group and can thus be used to study its structure.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Character theory is an essential tool in the classification of finite simple groups.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Close to half of the proof of the Feit–Thompson theorem involves intricate calculations with character values.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Let V be a finite-dimensional vector space over a field F and let *ρ* : *G* → GL(*V*) be a representation of a group G on V.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] A character *χρ* is called **irreducible** or **simple** if ρ is an irreducible representation.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The **degree** of the character χ is the dimension of ρ; in characteristic zero this is equal to the value *χ*(1).
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] A character of degree 1 is called **linear**.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] which is precisely the kernel of the representation ρ.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] However, the character is *not* a group homomorphism in general.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The irreducible complex characters of a finite group form a **character table** which encodes much useful information about the group G in a compact form.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Each row is labelled by an irreducible representation and the entries in the row are the characters of the representation on the respective conjugacy class of G.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The columns are labelled by (representatives of) the conjugacy classes of G.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] It is customary to label the first row by the character of the **trivial representation**, which is the trivial action of G on a 1-dimensional vector space by $\rho (g)=1$ for all $g\in G$ .
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Each entry in the first row is therefore 1.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Similarly, it is customary to label the first column by the identity.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Therefore, the first column contains the degree of each irreducible character.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] where ω is a primitive third root of unity.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The character table is always square, because the number of irreducible representations is equal to the number of conjugacy classes.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] where *β*(*g*) is the complex conjugate of *β*(*g*).
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] where the sum is over all of the irreducible characters *χi* of G and the symbol |*CG*(*g*)| denotes the order of the centralizer of g.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Note that since g and h are conjugate iff they are in the same column of the character table, this implies that the columns of the character table are orthogonal.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The character table does not in general determine the group up to isomorphism: for example, the quaternion group Q and the dihedral group of 8 elements, *D*4, have the same character table.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Brauer asked whether the character table, together with the knowledge of how the powers of elements of its conjugacy classes are distributed, determines a finite group up to isomorphism.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] In 1964, this was answered in the negative by E.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The linear representations of G are themselves a group under the tensor product, since the tensor product of 1-dimensional vector spaces is again 1-dimensional.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] This gives rise to a group of linear characters, called the character group under the operation $[\chi _{1}*\chi _{2}](g)=\chi _{1}(g)\chi _{2}(g)$ .
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] This group is connected to Dirichlet characters and Fourier analysis.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The characters discussed in this section are assumed to be complex-valued.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Let H be a subgroup of the finite group G.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Given a character χ of G, let *χH* denote its restriction to H.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Ferdinand Georg Frobenius showed how to construct a character of G from θ, using what is now known as *Frobenius reciprocity*.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] for each irreducible character χ of G (the leftmost inner product is for class functions of G and the rightmost inner product is for class functions of H).
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Since the restriction of a character of G to the subgroup H is again a character of H, this definition makes it clear that *θG* is a non-negative integer combination of irreducible characters of G, so is indeed a character of G.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] It is known as *the character of* G *induced from* θ.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The defining formula of Frobenius reciprocity can be extended to general complex-valued class functions.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Given a matrix representation ρ of H, Frobenius later gave an explicit way to construct a matrix representation of G, known as the representation induced from ρ, and written analogously as *ρG*.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] This led to an alternative description of the induced character *θG*.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] This induced character vanishes on all elements of G which are not conjugate to any element of H.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Since the induced character is a class function of G, it is only now necessary to describe its values on elements of H.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Because θ is a class function of H, this value does not depend on the particular choice of coset representatives.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] This alternative description of the induced character sometimes allows explicit computation from relatively little information about the embedding of H in G, and is often useful for calculation of particular character tables.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] When θ is the trivial character of H, the induced character obtained is known as the **permutation character** of G (on the cosets of H).
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The general technique of character induction and later refinements found numerous applications in finite group theory and elsewhere in mathematics, in the hands of mathematicians such as Emil Artin, Richard Brauer, Walter Feit and Michio Suzuki, as well as Frobenius himself.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The Mackey decomposition was defined and explored by George Mackey in the context of Lie groups, but is a powerful tool in the character theory and representation theory of finite groups.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Its basic form concerns the way a character (or module) induced from a subgroup H of a finite group G behaves on restriction back to a (possibly different) subgroup K of G, and makes use of the decomposition of G into (*H*, *K*)-double cosets.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] where *θt* is the class function of *t*−1*Ht* defined by *θt*(*t*−1*ht*) = *θ*(*h*) for all h in H.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] There is a similar formula for the restriction of an induced module to a subgroup, which holds for representations over any ring, and has applications in a wide variety of algebraic and topological contexts.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] (where T is a full set of (*H*, *K*)-double coset representatives, as before).
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] This formula is often used when θ and ψ are linear characters, in which case all the inner products appearing in the right hand sum are either 1 or 0, depending on whether or not the linear characters *θt* and ψ have the same restriction to *t*−1*Ht* ∩ *K*.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] If θ and ψ are both trivial characters, then the inner product simplifies to |*T*|.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] One may interpret the character of a representation as the "twisted" dimension of a vector space.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Treating the character as a function of the elements of the group *χ*(*g*), its value at the identity is the dimension of the space, since *χ*(1) = Tr(*ρ*(1)) = Tr(*IV*) = dim(*V*).
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Accordingly, one can view the other values of the character as "twisted" dimensions.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] One can find analogs or generalizations of statements about dimensions to statements about characters or representations.
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The character will satisfy $\chi _{\rho }(\operatorname {Ad} _{g}(X))=\chi _{\rho }(X)$ for all g in the associated Lie group G and all $X\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] Suppose now that ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is a complex semisimple Lie algebra with Cartan subalgebra ${\mathfrak {h}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The value of the character $\chi _{\rho }$ of an irreducible representation $\rho$ of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is determined by its values on ${\mathfrak {h}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] where the sum is over all weights $\lambda$ of $\rho$ and where $m_{\lambda }$ is the multiplicity of $\lambda$ .
[src:representation-theory/character-theory] The (restriction to ${\mathfrak {h}}$ of the) character can be computed more explicitly by the Weyl character formula.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] In chemistry, a group representation can relate mathematical group elements to symmetric rotations and reflections of molecules.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Representations of groups allow many group-theoretic problems to be reduced to problems in linear algebra.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] In physics, they describe how the symmetry group of a physical system affects the solutions of equations describing that system.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] The term *representation of a group* is also used in a more general sense to mean any "description" of a group as a group of transformations of some mathematical object.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] More formally, a "representation" means a homomorphism from the group to the automorphism group of an object.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] If the object is a vector space we have a *linear representation*.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Some people use *realization* for the general notion and reserve the term *representation* for the special case of linear representations.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] The bulk of this article describes linear representation theory; see the last section for generalizations.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] The representation theory of groups divides into subtheories depending on the kind of group being represented.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] The various theories are quite different in detail, though some basic definitions and concepts are similar.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Representation theory also depends heavily on the type of vector space on which the group acts.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] One distinguishes between finite-dimensional representations and infinite-dimensional ones.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] In the infinite-dimensional case, additional structures are important (e.g. whether or not the space is a Hilbert space, Banach space, etc.).
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] One must also consider the type of field over which the vector space is defined.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] The most important case is the field of complex numbers.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] The other important cases are the field of real numbers, finite fields, and fields of p-adic numbers.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] In general, algebraically closed fields are easier to handle than non-algebraically closed ones.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] The characteristic of the field is also significant; many theorems for finite groups depend on the characteristic of the field not dividing the order of the group.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] A **representation** of a group *G* on a vector space *V* over a field *K* is a group homomorphism from *G* to GL(*V*), the general linear group on *V*.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Here *V* is called the **representation space** and the dimension of *V* is called the **dimension** or **degree** of the representation.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] It is common practice to refer to *V* itself as the representation when the homomorphism is clear from the context.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] In the case where *V* is of finite dimension *n* it is common to choose a basis for *V* and identify GL(*V*) with GL(*n*, *K*), the group of $n\times n$ invertible matrices on the field *K*.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] } consisting only of the group's identity element.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] is an equivariant map which is an isomorphism of vector spaces.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Consider the complex number $u=e^{2\pi i/3}$ which has the property $u^{3}=1$ .
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] The set $C_{3}=\{1,u,u^{2}\}$ forms a cyclic group under multiplication.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] This representation is faithful because $\rho$ is a one-to-one map.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Then $S_{3}$ acts on V by permutation of the three variables.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] A subspace *W* of *V* that is invariant under the group action is called a *subrepresentation*.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] If *V* has exactly two subrepresentations, namely the zero-dimensional subspace and *V* itself, then the representation is said to be **irreducible**; if it has a proper subrepresentation of nonzero dimension, the representation is said to be **reducible**.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] The representation of dimension zero is considered to be neither reducible nor irreducible, just as the number 1 is considered to be neither composite nor prime.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Under the assumption that the characteristic of the field *K* does not divide the size of the group, representations of finite groups can be decomposed into a direct sum of irreducible subrepresentations (see Maschke's theorem).
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] This holds in particular for any representation of a finite group over the complex numbers, since the characteristic of the complex numbers is zero, which never divides the size of a group.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] In the example above, the first two representations given (ρ and σ) are both decomposable into two 1-dimensional subrepresentations (given by span{(1,0)} and span{(0,1)}), while the third representation (τ) is irreducible.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] This condition and the axioms for a group imply that ρ(*g*) is a bijection (or permutation) for all *g* in *G*.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Thus we may equivalently define a permutation representation to be a group homomorphism from G to the symmetric group S*X* of *X*.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] For more information on this topic see the article on group action.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Every group *G* can be viewed as a category with a single object; morphisms in this category are just the elements of *G*.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Given an arbitrary category *C*, a *representation* of *G* in *C* is a functor from *G* to *C*.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Such a functor selects an object *X* in *C* and a group homomorphism from *G* to Aut(*X*), the automorphism group of *X*.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] In the case where *C* is **Vect***K*, the category of vector spaces over a field *K*, this definition is equivalent to a linear representation.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Likewise, a set-theoretic representation is just a representation of *G* in the category of sets.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] When *C* is **Ab**, the category of abelian groups, the objects obtained are called *G*-modules.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] For another example consider the category of topological spaces, **Top**.
[src:representation-theory/group-representation] Representations in **Top** are homomorphisms from *G* to the homeomorphism group of a topological space *X*.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] Every finite-dimensional unitary representation on a Hilbert space V is the direct sum of irreducible representations.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] The structure analogous to an irreducible representation in the resulting theory is a simple module.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] Let $\rho$ be a representation i.e. a homomorphism $\rho :G\to GL(V)$ of a group G where V is a vector space over a field F .
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] If we pick a basis B for V , $\rho$ can be thought of as a function (a homomorphism) from a group into a set of invertible matrices and in this context is called a **matrix representation**.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] However, it simplifies things greatly if we think of the space V without a basis. $\rho$ is **d-dimensional** if the vector space V it acts over has dimension d .
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] A linear subspace $W\subset V$ is called **G -invariant** if $\rho (g)w\in W$ for all $g\in G$ and all $w\in W$ .
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] The co-restriction of $\rho$ to the general linear group of a G -invariant subspace $W\subset V$ is known as a **subrepresentation**.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] A representation $\rho :G\to GL(V)$ is said to be **irreducible** if it has only trivial subrepresentations (all representations can form a subrepresentation with the trivial G -invariant subspaces, e.g. the whole vector space V , and {0}).
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] If there is a proper nontrivial invariant subspace, $\rho$ is said to be **reducible**.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] Group elements can be represented by matrices, although the term "represented" has a specific and precise meaning in this context.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] A representation of a group is a mapping from the group elements to the general linear group of matrices.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] As notation, let *a*, *b*, *c*, ... denote elements of a group *G* with group product signified without any symbol, so *ab* is the group product of *a* and *b* and is also an element of *G*, and let representations be indicated by *D*.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] and similarly for all other group elements.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] The last two statements correspond to the requirement that *D* is a group homomorphism.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] A representation is reducible if it contains a nontrivial G-invariant subspace, that is to say, all the matrices $D(a)$ can be put in upper triangular block form by the same invertible matrix P .
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] which maps every matrix in the representation into the same pattern upper triangular blocks.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] Every ordered sequence minor block is a group subrepresentation.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] where $D^{(11)}(a)$ is a nontrivial subrepresentation.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] If we are able to find a matrix P that makes $D^{(12)}(a)=0$ as well, then $D(a)$ is not only reducible but also decomposable.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] A representation is decomposable if all the matrices $D(a)$ can be put in block-diagonal form by the same invertible matrix P .
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] which diagonalizes every matrix in the representation into the same pattern of diagonal blocks.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] Each such block is then a group subrepresentation independent from the others.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] The representations *D*(*a*) and *D′*(*a*) are said to be **equivalent representations**.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] so *D*(*a*) is **decomposable**, and it is customary to label the decomposed matrices by a superscript in brackets, as in *D*(*n*)(*a*) for *n* = 1, 2, ..., *k*, although some authors just write the numerical label without parentheses.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] *k* = 1, then the representation is indecomposable.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] An irreducible representation is by nature an indecomposable one.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] When the group G is finite, and K is a field with $char(K)\nmid |G|$ , then an indecomposable representation of G over K is an irreducible representation.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] In particular, this is true for $K=\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] All groups G have a one-dimensional, irreducible trivial representation by mapping all group elements to the identity transformation.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] Any one-dimensional representation is irreducible since it has no proper nontrivial invariant subspaces.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] The irreducible complex representations of a finite group G can be characterized using results from character theory.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] In particular, all complex representations decompose as a direct sum of irreps, and the number of irreps of G is equal to the number of conjugacy classes of G .
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] In quantum physics and quantum chemistry, each set of degenerate eigenstates of the Hamiltonian operator comprises a vector space V for a representation of the symmetry group of the Hamiltonian, a "multiplet", best studied through reduction to its irreducible parts.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] Identifying the irreducible representations therefore allows one to label the states, predict how they will split under perturbations; or transition to other states in V.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] Thus, in quantum mechanics, irreducible representations of the symmetry group of the system partially or completely label the energy levels of the system, allowing the selection rules to be determined.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] The irreps of *D*(**K**) and *D*(**J**), where **J** is the generator of rotations and **K** the generator of boosts, can be used to build to spin representations of the Lorentz group, because they are related to the spin matrices of quantum mechanics.
[src:representation-theory/irreducible-representation] This allows them to derive relativistic wave equations.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] In mathematics, **Maschke's theorem**, named after Heinrich Maschke, is a theorem in group representation theory that concerns the decomposition of representations of a finite group into irreducible pieces.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] Maschke's theorem allows one to make general conclusions about representations of a finite group *G* without actually computing them.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] It reduces the task of classifying all representations to a more manageable task of classifying irreducible representations, since when the theorem applies, any representation is a direct sum of irreducible pieces (constituents).
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] Moreover, it follows from the Jordan–Hölder theorem that, while the decomposition into a direct sum of irreducible subrepresentations may not be unique, the irreducible pieces have well-defined multiplicities.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] In particular, a representation of a finite group over a field of characteristic zero is determined up to isomorphism by its character.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] Maschke's theorem addresses the question: when is a general (finite-dimensional) representation built from irreducible subrepresentations using the direct sum operation?
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] This question (and its answer) are formulated differently for different perspectives on group representation theory.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] The vector space of complex-valued class functions of a group G has a natural G -invariant inner product structure, described in the article Schur orthogonality relations.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] Maschke's theorem was originally proved for the case of representations over $\mathbb {C}$ by constructing U as the orthogonal complement of W under this inner product.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] One of the approaches to representations of finite groups is through module theory.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] *Representations* of a group G are replaced by *modules* over its group algebra $K[G]$ (to be precise, there is an isomorphism of categories between $K[G]{\text{-Mod}}$ and $\operatorname {Rep} _{G}$ , the category of representations of G ).
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] Irreducible representations correspond to simple modules.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] In the module-theoretic language, Maschke's theorem asks: is an arbitrary module semisimple?
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] The importance of this result stems from the well developed theory of semisimple rings, in particular, their classification as given by the Wedderburn–Artin theorem.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] When K is the field of complex numbers, this shows that the algebra $K[G]$ is a product of several copies of complex matrix algebras, one for each irreducible representation.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] If the field K has characteristic zero, but is not algebraically closed, for example if K is the field of real or rational numbers, then a somewhat more complicated statement holds: the group algebra $K[G]$ is a product of matrix algebras over division rings over K .
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] The summands correspond to irreducible representations of G over K .
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] Let *U* be a subspace of *V* complement of *W*.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] so $w'\in \ker p$ implies that $hw'\in \ker p$ .
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] So the restriction of $\rho _{V}$ on $\ker p$ is also a representation.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] We will prove that *V* is a direct summand.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] Let *π* be any *K*-linear projection of *K*[*G*] onto *V*.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] Then *φ* is again a projection: it is clearly *K*-linear, maps *K*[*G*] to *V*, and induces the identity on *V* (therefore, maps *K*[*G*] onto *V*).
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] By the splitting lemma, $K[G]=V\oplus \ker \varphi$ .
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] This proves that every submodule is a direct summand, that is, *K*[*G*] is semisimple.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] The above proof depends on the fact that #*G* is invertible in *K*.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] This might lead one to ask if the converse of Maschke's theorem also holds: if the characteristic of *K* divides the order of *G*, does it follow that *K*[*G*] is not semisimple?
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] so that $sv$ is a nonzero element of both *I* and *V*.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] This proves *V* is not a direct complement of *I* for all *V*, so *K*[*G*] is not semisimple.
[src:representation-theory/maschke-s-theorem] The theorem can not apply to the case where *G* is infinite, or when the field *K* has characteristics dividing #*G*.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] The representation theory of groups is a part of mathematics which examines how groups act on given structures.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] Here the focus is in particular on operations of groups on vector spaces.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] Nevertheless, groups acting on other groups or on sets are also considered.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] For more details, please refer to the section on permutation representations.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] Other than a few marked exceptions, only finite groups will be considered in this article.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] We will also restrict ourselves to vector spaces over fields of characteristic zero.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] Because the theory of algebraically closed fields of characteristic zero is complete, a theory valid for a special algebraically closed field of characteristic zero is also valid for every other algebraically closed field of characteristic zero.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] Representation theory is used in many parts of mathematics, as well as in quantum chemistry and physics.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] Among other things it is used in algebra to examine the structure of groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] There are also applications in harmonic analysis and number theory.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] For example, representation theory is used in the modern approach to gain new results about automorphic forms.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] Let V be a K –vector space and G a finite group.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] A **linear representation** of G is a group homomorphism $\rho :G\to {\text{GL}}(V)={\text{Aut}}(V).$ Here ${\text{GL}}(V)$ is notation for a general linear group, and ${\text{Aut}}(V)$ for an automorphism group.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] The representation of a group in a module instead of a vector space is also called a linear representation.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] We write $(\rho ,V_{\rho })$ for the representation $\rho :G\to {\text{GL}}(V_{\rho })$ of $G.$ Sometimes we use the notation $(\rho ,V)$ if it is clear to which representation the space V belongs.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] In this article we will restrict ourselves to the study of finite-dimensional representation spaces, except for the last chapter.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] As in most cases only a finite number of vectors in V is of interest, it is sufficient to study the subrepresentation generated by these vectors.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] The representation space of this subrepresentation is then finite-dimensional.
