[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p01] A representation $\rho$ of a group G in a vector space endowed with an inner product is called **unitary** if $\rho (s)$ is unitary for every $s\in G.$ This means that in particular every $\rho (s)$ is diagonalizable.
