[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] As was shown in the section on properties of linear representations, we can - by restriction - obtain a representation of a subgroup starting from a representation of a group.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Naturally we are interested in the reverse process: Is it possible to obtain the representation of a group starting from a representation of a subgroup?
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] We will see that the induced representation defined below provides us with the necessary concept.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Admittedly, this construction is not inverse but rather adjoint to the restriction.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Let $\rho :G\to {\text{GL}}(V_{\rho })$ be a linear representation of $G.$ Let H be a subgroup and $\rho |_{H}$ the restriction.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Let W be a subrepresentation of $\rho _{H}.$ We write $\theta :H\to {\text{GL}}(W)$ to denote this representation.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] We denote the representation $\rho$ of G which is induced by the representation $\theta$ of H as $\rho ={\text{Ind}}_{H}^{G}(\theta ),$ or in short $\rho ={\text{Ind}}(\theta ),$ if there is no danger of confusion.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The results introduced in this section will be presented without proof.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Uniqueness and existence of the induced representation.
