[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Representation of the symmetric groups $S_{n}$ have been intensely studied.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Conjugacy classes in $S_{n}$ (and therefore, by the above, irreducible representations) correspond to partitions of *n*.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] For such a partition, a Young tableau is a graphical device depicting a partition.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The irreducible representation corresponding to such a partition (or Young tableau) is called a Specht module.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Representations of different symmetric groups are related: any representation of $S_{n}\times S_{m}$ yields a representation of $S_{n+m}$ by induction, and vice versa by restriction.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] inherits from these constructions the structure of a Hopf algebra which, it turns out, is closely related to symmetric functions.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] To a certain extent, the representations of the $GL_{n}(\mathbf {F} _{q})$ , as *n* varies, have a similar flavor as for the $S_{n}$ ; the above-mentioned induction process gets replaced by so-called parabolic induction.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] However, unlike for $S_{n}$ , where all representations can be obtained by induction of trivial representations, this is not true for $GL_{n}(\mathbf {F} _{q})$ .
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Instead, new building blocks, known as cuspidal representations, are needed.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Representations of $GL_{n}(\mathbf {F} _{q})$ and more generally, representations of finite groups of Lie type have been thoroughly studied.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Bonnafé (2010) describes the representations of $SL_{2}(\mathbf {F} _{q})$ .
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] A geometric description of irreducible representations of such groups, including the above-mentioned cuspidal representations, is obtained by Deligne-Lusztig theory, which constructs such representation in the l-adic cohomology of Deligne-Lusztig varieties.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The similarity of the representation theory of $S_{n}$ and $GL_{n}(\mathbf {F} _{q})$ goes beyond finite groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The philosophy of cusp forms highlights the kinship of representation theoretic aspects of these types of groups with general linear groups of local fields such as **Q***p* and of the ring of adeles, see Bump (2004).
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The theory of representations of compact groups may be, to some degree, extended to locally compact groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The representation theory unfolds in this context great importance for harmonic analysis and the study of automorphic forms.
