[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] A **topological group** is a group together with a topology with respect to which the group composition and the inversion are continuous.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Such a group is called **compact**, if any cover of $G,$ which is open in the topology, has a finite subcover.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Closed subgroups of a compact group are compact again.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Let G be a compact group and let V be a finite-dimensional $\mathbb {C}$ –vector space.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] A linear representation of G into a Banach space V is defined to be a continuous group homomorphism of G into the set of all bijective bounded linear operators on V with a continuous inverse.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] In the following, we will consider in particular representations of compact groups in Hilbert spaces.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Just as with finite groups, we can define the group algebra and the convolution algebra.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] However, the group algebra provides no helpful information in the case of infinite groups, because the continuity condition gets lost during the construction.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Instead the convolution algebra $L^{1}(G)$ takes its place.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Most properties of representations of finite groups can be transferred with appropriate changes to compact groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] All the definitions to representations of finite groups that are mentioned in the section ”Properties”, also apply to representations of compact groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] To define a subrepresentation we now need a closed subspace.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] This was not necessary for finite-dimensional representation spaces, because in this case every subspace is already closed.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] If T is unitary, the two representations are called **unitary equivalent**.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] To obtain a G –invariant inner product from a not G –invariant, we now have to use the integral over G instead of the sum.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] is a G –invariant inner product on V due to the properties of the Haar measure $dt.$ Thus, we can assume every representation on a Hilbert space to be unitary.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The map $s\mapsto L_{s}$ is a unitary representation of $G.$ It is called **left-regular representation**.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The **right-regular representation** is defined similarly.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] If G is infinite, these representations have no finite degree.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The left- and right-regular representation as defined at the beginning are isomorphic to the left- and right-regular representation as defined above, if the group G is finite.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The different ways of constructing new representations from given ones can be used for compact groups as well, except for the dual representation with which we will deal later.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The direct sum and the tensor product with a finite number of summands/factors are defined in exactly the same way as for finite groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] This is also the case for the symmetric and alternating square.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] However, we need a Haar measure on the direct product of compact groups in order to extend the theorem saying that the irreducible representations of the product of two groups are (up to isomorphism) exactly the tensor product of the irreducible representations of the factor groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] First, we note that the direct product $G_{1}\times G_{2}$ of two compact groups is again a compact group when provided with the product topology.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The Haar measure on the direct product is then given by the product of the Haar measures on the factor groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] For the dual representation on compact groups we require the topological dual $V'$ of the vector space $V.$ This is the vector space of all continuous linear functionals from the vector space V into the base field.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Thus, we can conclude that the dual representation is given by $\pi '(s)v'=v'\circ \pi (s^{-1})$ for all $v'\in V',s\in G.$ The map $\pi '$ is again a continuous group homomorphism and thus a representation.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] On Hilbert spaces: $\pi$ is irreducible if and only if $\pi '$ is irreducible.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Since the Haar measure is normalized, this inner product is unique.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Every representation of a compact group is isomorphic to a direct Hilbert sum of irreducible representations.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Note that the isotypes of not equivalent irreducible representations are pairwise orthogonal.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] passes through all the isomorphism classes of the irreducible representations.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] In general $\rho (s):V\to V$ is not G –linear.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] where we used the invariance of the Haar measure.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] If the representation is finite-dimensional, it is possible to determine the direct sum of the trivial subrepresentation just as in the case of finite groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Generally, representations of compact groups are investigated on Hilbert- and Banach spaces.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] In most cases they are not finite-dimensional.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Therefore, it is not useful to refer to characters when speaking about representations of compact groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Since irreducible representations of compact groups are finite-dimensional and unitary (see results from the first subsection), we can define irreducible characters in the same way as it was done for finite groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] As long as the constructed representations stay finite-dimensional, the characters of the newly constructed representations may be obtained in the same way as for finite groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Therefore, using the first theorem, the characters of irreducible representations of G form an orthonormal set on $L^{2}(G)$ with respect to this inner product.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] –times in the left-regular representation.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] As we already know that the non-isomorphic irreducible representations are orthonormal, we only need to verify that they generate $L^{2}(G).$ This may be done, by proving that there exists no non-zero square integrable function on G orthogonal to all the irreducible characters.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Just as in the case of finite groups, the number of the irreducible representations up to isomorphism of a group G equals the number of conjugacy classes of $G.$ However, because a compact group has in general infinitely many conjugacy classes, this does not provide any useful information.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] If H is a closed subgroup of finite index in a compact group $G,$ the definition of the induced representation for finite groups may be adopted.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The induced representation is then again a unitary representation.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The Frobenius reciprocity transfers, together with the modified definitions of the inner product and of the bilinear form, to compact groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The theorem now holds for square integrable functions on G instead of class functions, but the subgroup H must be closed.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Another important result in the representation theory of compact groups is the Peter-Weyl Theorem.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] It is usually presented and proven in harmonic analysis, as it represents one of its central and fundamental statements.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The Peter-Weyl Theorem (Second version).
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] The general features of the representation theory of a finite group *G*, over the complex numbers, were discovered by Ferdinand Georg Frobenius in the years before 1900.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory-of-finite-groups-p02] Later the modular representation theory of Richard Brauer was developed.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The algebraic objects amenable to such a description include groups, associative algebras and Lie algebras.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The most prominent of these (and historically the first) is the representation theory of groups, in which elements of a group are represented by invertible matrices such that the group operation is matrix multiplication.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Representation theory is a useful method because it reduces problems in abstract algebra to problems in linear algebra, a subject that is well understood.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Representations of more abstract objects in terms of familiar linear algebra can elucidate properties and simplify calculations within more abstract theories.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] For instance, representing a group by an infinite-dimensional Hilbert space allows methods of analysis to be applied to the theory of groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Furthermore, representation theory is important in physics because it can describe how the symmetry group of a physical system affects the solutions of equations describing that system.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Representation theory is pervasive across fields of mathematics.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The applications of representation theory are diverse.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] There are many approaches to representation theory: the same objects can be studied using methods from algebraic geometry, module theory, analytic number theory, differential geometry, operator theory, algebraic combinatorics and topology.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The success of representation theory has led to numerous generalizations.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] One of the most general is in category theory.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The algebraic objects to which representation theory applies can be viewed as particular kinds of categories, and the representations as functors from the object category to the category of vector spaces.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Let V be a vector space over a field $\mathbb {F}$ .
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] For instance, suppose V is $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ or $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ , the standard *n*-dimensional space of column vectors over the real or complex numbers, respectively.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In this case, the idea of representation theory is to do abstract algebra concretely by using $n\times n$ matrices of real or complex numbers.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] There are three main sorts of algebraic objects for which this can be done: groups, associative algebras and Lie algebras.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] There are two ways to define a representation.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The first uses the idea of an action, generalizing the way that matrices act on column vectors by matrix multiplication.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] A *representation* of a group G or (associative or Lie) algebra A on a vector space V is a map $\Phi \colon G\times V\to V\quad {\text{or}}\quad \Phi \colon A\times V\to V$ with two properties.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The definition for associative algebras is analogous, except that associative algebras do not always have an identity element, in which case equation (2.1) is omitted.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Equation (2.2) is an abstract expression of the associativity of matrix multiplication.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] This doesn't hold for the matrix commutator and also there is no identity element for the commutator.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] This approach is both more concise and more abstract.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The vector space *V* is called the **representation space** of *φ* and its dimension (if finite) is called the **dimension** of the representation (sometimes *degree*, as in ).
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] It is also common practice to refer to *V* itself as the representation when the homomorphism *φ* is clear from the context; otherwise the notation (*V*,*φ*) can be used to denote a representation.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] When *V* is of finite dimension *n*, one can choose a basis for *V* to identify *V* with **F***n*, and hence recover a matrix representation with entries in the field **F**.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] An effective or faithful representation is a representation (*V*,*φ*), for which the homomorphism *φ* is injective.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] If V and W are vector spaces over $\mathbb {F}$ , equipped with representations $\varphi$ and $\psi$ of a group G , then an **equivariant map** from V to W is a linear map $\alpha :V\rightarrow W$ such that $\alpha (g\cdot v)=g\cdot \alpha (v)$ for all g in G and v in V .
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Equivariant maps for representations of an associative or Lie algebra are defined similarly.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] If $\alpha$ is invertible, then it is said to be an isomorphism, in which case V and W (or, more precisely, $\varphi$ and $\psi$ ) are *isomorphic representations*, also phrased as *equivalent representations*.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] An equivariant map is often called an *intertwining map* of representations.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Also, in the case of a group G , it is on occasion called a G -map or G -linear map.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Isomorphic representations are, for practical purposes, "the same"; they provide the same information about the group or algebra being represented.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Representation theory therefore seeks to classify representations up to isomorphism.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The quotient space $V/W$ can also be made into a representation of G .
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] If V has exactly two subrepresentations, namely the trivial subspace {0} and V itself, then the representation is said to be ***irreducible***; if V has a proper nontrivial subrepresentation, the representation is said to be ***reducible***.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The definition of an irreducible representation implies Schur's lemma: an equivariant map ${\displaystyle \alpha$ between irreducible representations is either the zero map or an isomorphism, since its kernel and image are subrepresentations.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In particular, when $V=V'$ , this shows that the equivariant endomorphisms of V form an associative division algebra over the underlying field **F**.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] If **F** is algebraically closed, the only equivariant endomorphisms of an irreducible representation are the scalar multiples of the identity.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] There are counterexamples where a representation has a subrepresentation, but only has one non-trivial irreducible component.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The direct sum of two representations carries no more information about the group *G* than the two representations do individually.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] If a representation is the direct sum of two proper nontrivial subrepresentations, it is said to be decomposable.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Otherwise, it is said to be indecomposable.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In favorable circumstances, every finite-dimensional representation is a direct sum of irreducible representations: such representations are said to be semisimple.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In this case, it suffices to understand only the irreducible representations.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Examples where this "complete reducibility" phenomenon occurs (at least over fields of characteristic zero) include finite groups (see Maschke's theorem), compact groups, and semisimple Lie algebras.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In cases where complete reducibility does not hold, one must understand how indecomposable representations can be built from irreducible representations by using extensions of quotients by subrepresentations.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Suppose $\phi _{1}:G\rightarrow \mathrm {GL} (V_{1})$ and $\phi _{2}:G\rightarrow \mathrm {GL} (V_{2})$ are representations of a group G .
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] This product can be recognized as the coproduct on a coalgebra.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In general, the tensor product of irreducible representations is *not* irreducible; the process of decomposing a tensor product as a direct sum of irreducible representations is known as Clebsch–Gordan theory.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In the case of the representation theory of the group SU(2) (or equivalently, of its complexified Lie algebra $\mathrm {sl} (2;\mathbb {C} )$ ), the decomposition is easy to work out.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The irreducible representations are labeled by a parameter l that is a non-negative integer or half integer; the representation then has dimension $2l+1$ .
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Suppose we take the tensor product of the representation of two representations, with labels $l_{1}$ and $l_{2},$ where we assume $l_{1}\geq l_{2}$ .
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Then the tensor product decomposes as a direct sum of one copy of each representation with label l , where l ranges from $l_{1}-l_{2}$ to $l_{1}+l_{2}$ in increments of 1.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] If, for example, $l_{1}=l_{2}=1$ , then the values of l that occur are 0, 1, and 2.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Thus, the tensor product representation of dimension $(2l_{1}+1)\times (2l_{2}+1)=3\times 3=9$ decomposes as a direct sum of a 1-dimensional representation $(l=0),$ a 3-dimensional representation $(l=1),$ and a 5-dimensional representation $(l=2)$ .
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Representation theory is notable for the number of branches it has, and the diversity of the approaches to studying representations of groups and algebras.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Although, all the theories have in common the basic concepts discussed already, they differ considerably in detail.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Representation theory depends upon the nature of the vector space on which the algebraic object is represented.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The most important distinction is between finite-dimensional representations and infinite-dimensional ones.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In the infinite-dimensional case, additional structures are important (for example, whether or not the space is a Hilbert space, Banach space, etc.).
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Additional algebraic structures can also be imposed in the finite-dimensional case.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Representation theory depends upon the type of field over which the vector space is defined.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The most important cases are the field of complex numbers, the field of real numbers, finite fields, and fields of p-adic numbers.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Additional difficulties arise for fields of positive characteristic and for fields that are not algebraically closed.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Group representations are a very important tool in the study of finite groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] They also arise in the applications of finite group theory to geometry and crystallography.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Representations of finite groups exhibit many of the features of the general theory and point the way to other branches and topics in representation theory.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Over a field of characteristic zero, the representation of a finite group *G* has a number of convenient properties.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] First, the representations of *G* are semisimple (completely reducible).
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] This is a consequence of Maschke's theorem, which states that any subrepresentation *V* of a *G*-representation *W* has a *G*-invariant complement.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] An irreducible representation of *G* is completely determined by its character.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Maschke's theorem holds more generally for fields of positive characteristic *p*, such as the finite fields, as long as the prime *p* is coprime to the order of *G*.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] When *p* and |*G*| have a common factor, there are *G*-representations that are not semisimple, which are studied in a subbranch called modular representation theory.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Hence any *G*-representation is unitary.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Unitary representations are automatically semisimple, since Maschke's result can be proven by taking the orthogonal complement of a subrepresentation.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] When studying representations of groups that are not finite, the unitary representations provide a good generalization of the real and complex representations of a finite group.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Results such as Maschke's theorem and the unitary property that rely on averaging can be generalized to more general groups by replacing the average with an integral, provided that a suitable notion of integral can be defined.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] This can be done for compact topological groups (including compact Lie groups), using Haar measure, and the resulting theory is known as abstract harmonic analysis.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Over arbitrary fields, another class of finite groups that have a good representation theory are the finite groups of Lie type.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Important examples are linear algebraic groups over finite fields.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The representation theory of linear algebraic groups and Lie groups extends these examples to infinite-dimensional groups, the latter being intimately related to Lie algebra representations.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The importance of character theory for finite groups has an analogue in the theory of weights for representations of Lie groups and Lie algebras.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Modular representations of a finite group *G* are representations over a field whose characteristic is not coprime to |*G*|, so that Maschke's theorem no longer holds (because |*G*| is not invertible in **F** and so one cannot divide by it).
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] As well as having applications to group theory, modular representations arise naturally in other branches of mathematics, such as algebraic geometry, coding theory, combinatorics and number theory.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] A unitary representation of a group *G* is a linear representation *φ* of *G* on a real or (usually) complex Hilbert space *V* such that *φ*(*g*) is a unitary operator for every *g* ∈ *G*.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Such representations have been widely applied in quantum mechanics since the 1920s, thanks in particular to the influence of Hermann Weyl, and this has inspired the development of the theory, most notably through the analysis of representations of the Poincaré group by Eugene Wigner.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] One of the pioneers in constructing a general theory of unitary representations (for any group *G* rather than just for particular groups useful in applications) was George Mackey, and an extensive theory was developed by Harish-Chandra and others in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] A major goal is to describe the "unitary dual", the space of irreducible unitary representations of *G*.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The theory is most well-developed in the case that *G* is a locally compact (Hausdorff) topological group and the representations are strongly continuous.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] For *G* abelian, the unitary dual is just the space of characters, while for *G* compact, the Peter–Weyl theorem shows that the irreducible unitary representations are finite-dimensional and the unitary dual is discrete.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] For example, if *G* is the circle group *S*1, then the characters are given by integers, and the unitary dual is **Z**.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] For non-compact *G*, the question of which representations are unitary is a subtle one.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Although irreducible unitary representations must be "admissible" (as Harish-Chandra modules) and it is easy to detect which admissible representations have a nondegenerate invariant sesquilinear form, it is hard to determine when this form is positive definite.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] An effective description of the unitary dual, even for relatively well-behaved groups such as real reductive Lie groups (discussed below), remains an important open problem in representation theory.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] It has been solved for many particular groups, such as SL(2,**R**) and the Lorentz group.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Thus unitary representation theory and harmonic analysis are intimately related, and abstract harmonic analysis exploits this relationship, by developing the analysis of functions on locally compact topological groups and related spaces.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] A major goal is to provide a general form of the Fourier transform and the Plancherel theorem.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] This is done by constructing a measure on the unitary dual and an isomorphism between the regular representation of *G* on the space L2(*G*) of square integrable functions on *G* and its representation on the space of L2 functions on the unitary dual.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Pontrjagin duality and the Peter–Weyl theorem achieve this for abelian and compact *G* respectively.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Another approach involves considering all unitary representations, not just the irreducible ones.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] These form a category, and Tannaka–Krein duality provides a way to recover a compact group from its category of unitary representations.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] If the group is neither abelian nor compact, no general theory is known with an analogue of the Plancherel theorem or Fourier inversion, although Alexander Grothendieck extended Tannaka–Krein duality to a relationship between linear algebraic groups and tannakian categories.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Harmonic analysis has also been extended from the analysis of functions on a group *G* to functions on homogeneous spaces for *G*.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The theory is particularly well developed for symmetric spaces and provides a theory of automorphic forms (discussed below).
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] A Lie group is a group that is also a smooth manifold.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Many classical groups of matrices over the real or complex numbers are Lie groups.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Many of the groups important in physics and chemistry are Lie groups, and their representation theory is crucial to the application of group theory in those fields.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The representation theory of Lie groups can be developed first by considering the compact groups, to which results of compact representation theory apply.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] This theory can be extended to finite-dimensional representations of semisimple Lie groups using Weyl's unitary trick: each semisimple real Lie group *G* has a complexification, which is a complex Lie group *G*c, and this complex Lie group has a maximal compact subgroup *K*.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The finite-dimensional representations of *G* closely correspond to those of *K*.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] A general Lie group is a semidirect product of a solvable Lie group and a semisimple Lie group (the Levi decomposition).
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The classification of representations of solvable Lie groups is intractable in general, but often easy in practical cases.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Representations of semidirect products can then be analysed by means of general results called *Mackey theory*, which is a generalization of the methods used in Wigner's classification of representations of the Poincaré group.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] A Lie algebra over a field **F** is a vector space over **F** equipped with a skew-symmetric bilinear operation called the Lie bracket, which satisfies the Jacobi identity.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Lie algebras arise in particular as tangent spaces to Lie groups at the identity element, leading to their interpretation as "infinitesimal symmetries".
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] An important approach to the representation theory of Lie groups is to study the corresponding representation theory of Lie algebras, but representations of Lie algebras also have an intrinsic interest.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Lie algebras, like Lie groups, have a Levi decomposition into semisimple and solvable parts, with the representation theory of solvable Lie algebras being intractable in general.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In contrast, the finite-dimensional representations of semisimple Lie algebras are completely understood, after work of Élie Cartan.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] A representation of a semisimple Lie algebra 𝖌 is analysed by choosing a Cartan subalgebra, which is essentially a generic maximal subalgebra 𝖍 of 𝖌 on which the Lie bracket is zero ("abelian").
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The representation of 𝖌 can be decomposed into weight spaces that are eigenspaces for the action of 𝖍 and the infinitesimal analogue of characters.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The structure of semisimple Lie algebras then reduces the analysis of representations to easily understood combinatorics of the possible weights that can occur.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] There are many classes of infinite-dimensional Lie algebras whose representations have been studied.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Among these, an important class are the Kac–Moody algebras.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] They are named after Victor Kac and Robert Moody, who independently discovered them.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] These algebras form a generalization of finite-dimensional semisimple Lie algebras, and share many of their combinatorial properties.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] This means that they have a class of representations that can be understood in the same way as representations of semisimple Lie algebras.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Affine Lie algebras are a special case of Kac–Moody algebras, which have particular importance in mathematics and theoretical physics, especially conformal field theory and the theory of exactly solvable models.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Kac discovered an elegant proof of certain combinatorial identities, Macdonald identities, which is based on the representation theory of affine Kac–Moody algebras.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Lie superalgebras are generalizations of Lie algebras in which the underlying vector space has a **Z**2-grading, and skew-symmetry and Jacobi identity properties of the Lie bracket are modified by signs.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Their representation theory is similar to the representation theory of Lie algebras.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Linear algebraic groups (or more generally, affine group schemes) are analogues in algebraic geometry of Lie groups, but over more general fields than just **R** or **C**.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In particular, over finite fields, they give rise to finite groups of Lie type.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Invariant theory studies actions on algebraic varieties from the point of view of their effect on functions, which form representations of the group.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Classically, the theory dealt with the question of explicit description of polynomial functions that do not change, or are *invariant*, under the transformations from a given linear group.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The modern approach analyses the decomposition of these representations into irreducibles.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Invariant theory of infinite groups is inextricably linked with the development of linear algebra, especially, the theories of quadratic forms and determinants.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Another subject with strong mutual influence is projective geometry, where invariant theory can be used to organize the subject, and during the 1960s, new life was breathed into the subject by David Mumford in the form of his geometric invariant theory.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Modern developments link representation theory and invariant theory to areas as diverse as holonomy, differential operators and the theory of several complex variables.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Automorphic forms are a generalization of modular forms to more general analytic functions, perhaps of several complex variables, with similar transformation properties.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The generalization involves replacing the modular group PSL2 (**R**) and a chosen congruence subgroup by a semisimple Lie group *G* and a discrete subgroup Γ.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Just as modular forms can be viewed as differential forms on a quotient of the upper half space ***H*** = PSL2 (**R**)/SO(2), automorphic forms can be viewed as differential forms (or similar objects) on Γ\*G*/*K*, where *K* is (typically) a maximal compact subgroup of *G*.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Some care is required, however, as the quotient typically has singularities.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The quotient of a semisimple Lie group by a compact subgroup is a symmetric space and so the theory of automorphic forms is intimately related to harmonic analysis on symmetric spaces.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Before the development of the general theory, many important special cases were worked out in detail, including the Hilbert modular forms and Siegel modular forms.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Important results in the theory include the Selberg trace formula and the realization by Robert Langlands that the Riemann–Roch theorem could be applied to calculate the dimension of the space of automorphic forms.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The subsequent notion of "automorphic representation" has proved of great technical value for dealing with the case that *G* is an algebraic group, treated as an adelic algebraic group.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] As a result, an entire philosophy, the Langlands program has developed around the relation between representation and number theoretic properties of automorphic forms.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In one sense, associative algebra representations generalize both representations of groups and Lie algebras.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] A representation of a group induces a representation of a corresponding group ring or group algebra, while representations of a Lie algebra correspond bijectively to representations of its universal enveloping algebra.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] However, the representation theory of general associative algebras does not have all of the nice properties of the representation theory of groups and Lie algebras.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] When considering representations of an associative algebra, one can forget the underlying field, and simply regard the associative algebra as a ring, and its representations as modules.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] This approach is surprisingly fruitful: many results in representation theory can be interpreted as special cases of results about modules over a ring.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Hopf algebras provide a way to improve the representation theory of associative algebras, while retaining the representation theory of groups and Lie algebras as special cases.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In particular, the tensor product of two representations is a representation, as is the dual vector space.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The Hopf algebras associated to groups have a commutative algebra structure, and so general Hopf algebras are known as quantum groups, although this term is often restricted to certain Hopf algebras arising as deformations of groups or their universal enveloping algebras.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The representation theory of quantum groups has added surprising insights to the representation theory of Lie groups and Lie algebras, for instance through the crystal basis of Kashiwara.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] This condition and the axioms for a group imply that *ρ*(*g*) is a bijection (or permutation) for all *g* in *G*.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In the case where *C* is **Vect****F**, the category of vector spaces over a field **F**, this definition is equivalent to a linear representation.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Since groups are categories, one can also consider representation of other categories.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] The simplest generalization is to monoids, which are categories with one object.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Groups are monoids for which every morphism is invertible.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] General monoids have representations in any category.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In the category of sets, these are monoid actions, but monoid representations on vector spaces and other objects can be studied.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] More generally, one can relax the assumption that the category being represented has only one object.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] In full generality, this is simply the theory of functors between categories, and little can be said.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] One special case has had a significant impact on representation theory, namely the representation theory of quivers.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] A quiver is simply a directed graph (with loops and multiple arrows allowed), but it can be made into a category (and also an algebra) by considering paths in the graph.
[src:representation-theory/representation-theory] Representations of such categories/algebras have illuminated several aspects of representation theory, for instance by allowing non-semisimple representation theory questions about a group to be reduced in some cases to semisimple representation theory questions about a quiver.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] In mathematics, **Schur's lemma** is an elementary but useful statement in representation theory of groups and algebras.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] In the group case it says that if *M* and *N* are two finite-dimensional irreducible representations of a group *G* and *φ* is a linear map from *M* to *N* that commutes with the action of the group, then either *φ* is invertible, or *φ* = 0.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] An important special case occurs when *M* = *N*, i.e.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] *φ* is a self-map; in particular, for representations over an algebraically closed field (e.g. $\mathbb {C}$ ), any element of the center of a group must act as a scalar operator (a scalar multiple of the identity) on *M*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] The lemma is named after Issai Schur who used it to prove the Schur orthogonality relations and develop the basics of the representation theory of finite groups.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Schur's lemma admits generalisations to Lie groups and Lie algebras, the most common of which are due to Jacques Dixmier and Daniel Quillen.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Representation theory is the study of homomorphisms from a group, *G*, into the general linear group *GL*(*V*) of a vector space *V*; i.e., into the group of automorphisms of *V*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] (Let us here restrict ourselves to the case when the underlying field of *V* is $\mathbb {C}$ , the field of complex numbers.) Such a homomorphism is called a representation of *G* on *V*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] A representation on *V* is a special case of a group action on *V*, but rather than permit any arbitrary bijections (permutations) of the underlying set of *V*, we restrict ourselves to invertible *linear* transformations.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Let *ρ* be a representation of *G* on *V*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] It may be the case that *V* has a subspace, *W*, such that for every element *g* of *G*, the invertible linear map *ρ*(*g*) preserves or fixes *W*, so that (*ρ*(*g*))(*w*) is in *W* for every *w* in *W*, and (*ρ*(*g*))(*v*) is not in *W* for any *v* not in *W*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] In other words, every linear map *ρ*(*g*): *V*→*V* is also an automorphism of *W*, *ρ*(*g*): *W*→*W*, when its domain is restricted to *W*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] We say *W* is *stable* under *G*, or stable under the action of *G*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] It is clear that if we consider *W* on its own as a vector space, then there is an obvious representation of *G* on *W*—the representation we get by restricting each map *ρ*(*g*) to *W*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] When *W* has this property, we call *W* with the given representation a *subrepresentation* of *V*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Every representation of *G* has itself and the zero vector space as trivial subrepresentations.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] A representation of *G* with no non-trivial subrepresentations is called an *irreducible representation*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Irreducible representations – like the prime numbers, or like the simple groups in group theory – are the building blocks of representation theory.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Many of the initial questions and theorems of representation theory deal with the properties of irreducible representations.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Just as we are interested in homomorphisms between groups, and in continuous maps between topological spaces, we are also interested in certain functions between representations of *G*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Let *V* and *W* be vector spaces, and let $\rho _{V}$ and $\rho _{W}$ be representations of *G* on *V* and *W* respectively.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Then we define a *G*-linear map *f* from *V* to *W* to be a linear map from *V* to *W* that is equivariant under the action of *G*; that is, for every *g* in *G*, $\rho _{W}(g)\circ f=f\circ \rho _{V}(g)$ .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] In other words, we require that *f* commutes with the action of *G*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] *G*-linear maps are the morphisms in the category of representations of *G*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Schur's Lemma is a theorem that describes what *G*-linear maps can exist between two irreducible representations of *G*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] If $V=W$ finite-dimensional over an algebraically closed field (e.g. $\mathbb {C}$ ); and if $\rho _{V}=\rho _{W}$ , then the only nontrivial *G*-linear maps are the identity, and scalar multiples of the identity.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] But saying that $f(\rho _{V}(g)(x))=0$ is the same as saying that $\rho _{V}(g)(x)$ is in the null space of $f:V\rightarrow W$ .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] So $V'$ is stable under the action of *G*; it is a subrepresentation.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Since by assumption V is irreducible, $V'$ must be zero; so f is injective.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] So the image of $f(x)$ is a subspace $W'$ of W stable under the action of G , so it is a subrepresentation and f must be zero or surjective.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] By assumption it is not zero, so it is surjective, in which case it is an isomorphism.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] In the event that $V=W$ finite-dimensional over an algebraically closed field and they have the same representation, let $\lambda$ be an eigenvalue of f .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] (An eigenvalue exists for every linear transformation on a finite-dimensional vector space over an algebraically closed field.) Let $f'=f-\lambda I$ .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Then if x is an eigenvector of f corresponding to $\lambda ,f'(x)=0$ .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] It is clear that $f'$ is a *G*-linear map, because the sum or difference of *G*-linear maps is also *G*-linear.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Then we return to the above argument, where we used the fact that a map was *G*-linear to conclude that the kernel is a subrepresentation, and is thus either zero or equal to all of V ; because it is not zero (it contains x ) it must be all of *V* and so $f'$ is trivial, so $f=\lambda I$ .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] An important corollary of Schur's lemma follows from the observation that we can often build explicitly G -linear maps between representations by "averaging" over the action of individual group elements on some fixed linear operator.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] In particular, given any irreducible representation, such objects will satisfy the assumptions of Schur's lemma, hence be scalar multiples of the identity.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] If $V=W$ is finite-dimensional over an algebraically closed field (e.g. $\mathbb {C}$ ); and if $\rho _{V}=\rho _{W}$ , then $h_{0}=I\,\mathrm {Tr} [h]/n$ , where *n* is the dimension of *V*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] That is, $h_{0}$ is a homothety of ratio $\mathrm {Tr} [h]/n$ .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Now applying the previous theorem, for case 1, it follows that $h_{0}=0$ , and for case 2, it follows that $h_{0}$ is a scalar multiple of the identity matrix (i.e., $h_{0}=\mu I$ ).
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] It then follows that $\mu =\mathrm {Tr} [h]/n$ .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] For example, in the context of quantum information science, it is used to derive results about complex projective t-designs.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] In the context of molecular orbital theory, it is used to restrict atomic orbital interactions based on the molecular symmetry.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] The group version is a special case of the module version, since any representation of a group *G* can equivalently be viewed as a module over the group ring of *G*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Schur's lemma is frequently applied in the following particular case.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Suppose that *R* is an algebra over a field *k* and the vector space *M* = *N* is a simple module of *R*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Then Schur's lemma says that the endomorphism ring of the module *M* is a division algebra over *k*.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] If *M* is finite-dimensional, this division algebra is finite-dimensional.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] If *k* is the field of complex numbers, the only option is that this division algebra is the complex numbers.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Thus the endomorphism ring of the module *M* is "as small as possible".
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] In other words, the only linear transformations of *M* that commute with all transformations coming from *R* are scalar multiples of the identity.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] More generally, if R is an algebra over an algebraically closed field k and M is a simple R -module satisfying $\dim _{k}(M)<\#k$ (the cardinality of k ), then $\operatorname {End} _{R}(M)=k$ .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] So in particular, if R is an algebra over an uncountable algebraically closed field k and M is a simple module that is at most countably-dimensional, the only linear transformations of M that commute with all transformations coming from R are scalar multiples of the identity.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] When the field is not algebraically closed, the case where the endomorphism ring is as small as possible is still of particular interest.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] A simple module over a k -algebra is said to be absolutely simple if its endomorphism ring is isomorphic to k .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] This is in general stronger than being irreducible over the field k , and implies the module is irreducible even over the algebraic closure of k .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] If $\operatorname {End} _{R}(M)=k$ , say in the case sketched above, every element of $Z(R)$ acts on M as an R -endomorphism and hence as a scalar.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Thus, there is a ring homomorphism $\chi :Z(R)\to k$ such that $(z-\chi (z))m=0$ for all $z\in Z(R),m\in M$ .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] In particular, M has central character $\chi$ .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] In the case where $k=\mathbb {C} ,R=\mathbb {C} [G]$ is the group algebra of a finite group G , the same conclusion follows.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Here, the center of R consists of elements of the shape $\sum _{g\in G}a(g)g$ where $a:G\to \mathbb {C}$ is a class function, i.e. invariant under conjugation.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Since the set of class functions is spanned by the characters $\chi _{\pi }$ of the irreducible representations $\pi \in {\hat {G}}$ , the central character is determined by what it maps $u_{\pi }:={\frac {1}{\#G}}\sum _{g\in G}\chi _{\pi }(g)g$ to (for all $\pi \in {\hat {G}}$ ).
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Since all $u_{\pi }$ are idempotent, they are each mapped either to 0 or to 1, and since $u_{\pi }u_{\pi '}=0$ for two different irreducible representations, only one $u_{\pi }$ can be mapped to 1: the one corresponding to the module M .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] We now describe Schur's lemma as it is usually stated in the context of representations of Lie groups and Lie algebras.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] First, suppose that $V_{1}$ and $V_{2}$ are irreducible representations of a Lie group or Lie algebra over any field and that $\phi :V_{1}\rightarrow V_{2}$ is an intertwining map.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Then $\phi$ is either zero or an isomorphism.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Second, if V is an irreducible representation of a Lie group or Lie algebra over an *algebraically closed* field and $\phi :V\rightarrow V$ is an intertwining map, then $\phi$ is a scalar multiple of the identity map.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Third, suppose $V_{1}$ and $V_{2}$ are irreducible representations of a Lie group or Lie algebra over an *algebraically closed* field and $\phi _{1},\phi _{2}:V_{1}\rightarrow V_{2}$ are nonzero intertwining maps.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] A simple corollary of the second statement is that every complex irreducible representation of an abelian group is one-dimensional.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Suppose ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is a Lie algebra and $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ is the universal enveloping algebra of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Let ${\displaystyle \pi$ be an irreducible representation of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ over an algebraically closed field.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] The universal property of the universal enveloping algebra ensures that $\pi$ extends to a representation of $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ acting on the same vector space.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] It follows from the second part of Schur's lemma that if x belongs to the center of $U({\mathfrak {g}})$ , then $\pi (x)$ must be a multiple of the identity operator.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] In the case when ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is a complex semisimple Lie algebra, an important example of the preceding construction is the one in which x is the (quadratic) Casimir element C .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] In this case, $\pi (C)=\lambda _{\pi }I$ , where $\lambda _{\pi }$ is a constant that can be computed explicitly in terms of the highest weight of $\pi$ .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] The action of the Casimir element plays an important role in the proof of complete reducibility for finite-dimensional representations of semisimple Lie algebras.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] The one-module version of Schur's lemma admits generalizations for modules M that are not necessarily simple.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] They express relations between the module-theoretic properties of M and the properties of the endomorphism ring of M .
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Schur's lemma cannot be reversed in general, however, since there exist modules that are not simple but whose endomorphism algebra is a division ring.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Such modules are necessarily indecomposable and so cannot exist over semisimple rings, such as the complex group ring of a finite group.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] However, even over the ring of integers, the module of rational numbers has an endomorphism ring that is a division ring, specifically the field of rational numbers.
[src:representation-theory/schur-s-lemma] Even for group rings, there are examples when the characteristic of the field divides the order of the group: the Jacobson radical of the projective cover of the one-dimensional representation of the alternating group A5 over the finite field with three elements F3 has F3 as its endomorphism ring.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] In the mathematical field of representation theory, the concept of **weights** of an algebra *A* over a field **F** is a generalisation of that of eigenvalues.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] They are algebra homomorphisms from *A* to **F**, or equivalently, one-dimensional representations of *A* over **F**.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] It is the algebra analogue of a multiplicative character of a group.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The importance of the concept, however, stems from its application to representations of Lie algebras and hence also to representations of algebraic and Lie groups.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] In this context, a **weight of a representation** is a generalization of the notion of an eigenvalue, and the corresponding eigenspace is called a **weight space**.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Given a set *S* of $n\times n$ matrices over the same field, each of which is diagonalizable, and any two of which commute, it is always possible to simultaneously diagonalize all of the elements of *S*.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Equivalently, for any set *S* of mutually commuting semisimple linear transformations of a finite-dimensional vector space *V* there exists a basis of *V* consisting of *simultaneous eigenvectors* of all elements of *S*.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Each of these common eigenvectors *v* ∈ *V* defines a linear functional on the subalgebra *U* of End(*V* ) generated by the set of endomorphisms *S*; this functional is defined as the map which associates to each element of *U* its eigenvalue on the eigenvector *v*.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] This map is also multiplicative, and sends the identity to 1; thus it is an algebra homomorphism from *U* to the base field.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] This "generalized eigenvalue" is a prototype for the notion of a weight.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The notion is closely related to the idea of a multiplicative character in group theory, which is a homomorphism *χ* from a group *G* to the multiplicative group of a field **F**.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Indeed, if *G* acts on a vector space *V* over **F**, each simultaneous eigenspace for every element of *G*, if such exists, determines a multiplicative character on *G*: the eigenvalue on this common eigenspace of each element of the group.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] If an algebra *A* acts on a vector space *V* over **F** to any simultaneous eigenspace, this corresponds an algebra homomorphism from *A* to **F** assigning to each element of *A* its eigenvalue.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Any weight on a Lie algebra **g** vanishes on the derived algebra [**g**,**g**] and hence descends to a weight on the abelian Lie algebra **g**/[**g**,**g**].
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Thus weights are primarily of interest for abelian Lie algebras, where they reduce to the simple notion of a generalized eigenvalue for space of commuting linear transformations.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] If *G* is a Lie group or an algebraic group, then a multiplicative character θ: *G* → **F**× induces a weight *χ* = dθ: **g** → **F** on its Lie algebra by differentiation.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Let ${\mathfrak {g}}$ be a complex semisimple Lie algebra and ${\mathfrak {h}}$ a Cartan subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] In this section, we describe the concepts needed to formulate the "theorem of the highest weight" classifying the finite-dimensional representations of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Notably, we will explain the notion of a "dominant integral element." The representations themselves are described in the article linked to above.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] A **weight** of the representation *V* (the representation is often referred to in short by the vector space *V* over which elements of the Lie algebra act rather than the map $\sigma$ ) is a linear functional λ such that the corresponding weight space is nonzero.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Nonzero elements of the weight space are called **weight vectors**.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] That is to say, a weight vector is a simultaneous eigenvector for the action of the elements of ${\mathfrak {h}}$ , with the corresponding eigenvalues given by λ.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] then *V* is called a *weight module;* this corresponds to there being a common eigenbasis (a basis of simultaneous eigenvectors) for all the represented elements of the algebra, i.e., to there being simultaneously diagonalizable matrices (see diagonalizable matrix).
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] If *G* is a Lie group with Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , every finite-dimensional representation of *G* induces a representation of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] A weight of the representation of *G* is then simply a weight of the associated representation of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] There is a subtle distinction between weights of group representations and Lie algebra representations, which is that there is a different notion of integrality condition in the two cases; see below.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] For the adjoint representation $\mathrm {ad$ of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , the space over which the representation acts is the Lie algebra itself.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Then the nonzero weights are called **roots**, the weight spaces are called **root spaces**, and the weight vectors, which are thus elements of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , are called **root vectors**.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The collection of roots forms a root system.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] That is, $\sigma (X)(v)$ is either the zero vector or a weight vector with weight $\lambda +\alpha$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Thus, the action of X maps the weight space with weight $\lambda$ into the weight space with weight $\lambda +\alpha$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] For example, if ${\mathfrak {g}}={\mathfrak {su}}_{\mathbb {C} }(2)$ , or ${\mathfrak {su}}(2)$ complexified, the root vectors ${H,X,Y}$ span the algebra and have weights 0 , 1 , and $-1$ respectively.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The Cartan subalgebra is spanned by H , and the action of H classifies the weight spaces.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The action of X maps a weight space of weight $\lambda$ to the weight space of weight $\lambda +1$ and the action of Y maps a weight space of weight $\lambda$ to the weight space of weight $\lambda -1$ , and the action of H maps the weight spaces to themselves.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Let ${\mathfrak {h}}_{0}^{*}$ be the real subspace of ${\mathfrak {h}}^{*}$ generated by the roots of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , where ${\mathfrak {h}}^{*}$ is the space of linear functionals ${\displaystyle \lambda$ , the dual space to ${\mathfrak {h}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] For computations, it is convenient to choose an inner product that is invariant under the Weyl group, that is, under reflections about the hyperplanes orthogonal to the roots.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] We may then use this inner product to identify ${\mathfrak {h}}_{0}^{*}$ with a subspace ${\mathfrak {h}}_{0}$ of ${\mathfrak {h}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] We now define two different notions of integrality for elements of ${\mathfrak {h}}_{0}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The motivation for this condition is that the coroot $H_{\alpha }$ can be identified with the *H* element in a standard ${X,Y,H}$ basis for an $sl(2,\mathbb {C} )$ -subalgebra of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] By elementary results for $sl(2,\mathbb {C} )$ , the eigenvalues of $H_{\alpha }$ in any finite-dimensional representation must be an integer.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] We conclude that, as stated above, the weight of any finite-dimensional representation of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is algebraically integral.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The **fundamental weights** $\omega _{1},\ldots ,\omega _{n}$ are defined by the property that they form a basis of ${\mathfrak {h}}_{0}$ dual to the set of coroots associated to the simple roots.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] where $\alpha _{1},\ldots \alpha _{n}$ are the simple roots.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] An element $\lambda$ is then algebraically integral if and only if it is an integral combination of the fundamental weights.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The set of all ${\mathfrak {g}}$ -integral weights is a lattice in ${\mathfrak {h}}_{0}$ called the *weight lattice* for ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , denoted by $P({\mathfrak {g}})$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The figure shows the example of the Lie algebra $sl(3,\mathbb {C} )$ , whose root system is the $A_{2}$ root system.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] There are two simple roots, $\gamma _{1}$ and $\gamma _{2}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The first fundamental weight, $\omega _{1}$ , should be orthogonal to $\gamma _{2}$ and should project orthogonally to half of $\gamma _{1}$ , and similarly for $\omega _{2}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The weight lattice is then the triangular lattice.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Suppose now that the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is the Lie algebra of a Lie group *G*.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Then we say that $\lambda \in {\mathfrak {h}}_{0}$ is **analytically integral** (*G-integral*) if for each *t* in ${\mathfrak {h}}$ such that $\exp(t)=1\in G$ we have $(\lambda ,t)\in 2\pi i\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The reason for making this definition is that if a representation of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ arises from a representation of *G*, then the weights of the representation will be *G*-integral.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] For *G* semisimple, the set of all *G*-integral weights is a sublattice *P*(*G*) ⊂ *P*( ${\mathfrak {g}}$ ).
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] If *G* is not simply connected, then the lattice *P*(*G*) is smaller than *P*( ${\mathfrak {g}}$ ) and their quotient is isomorphic to the fundamental group of *G*.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] We now introduce a partial ordering on the set of weights, which will be used to formulate the theorem of the highest weight describing the representations of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Recall that *R* is the set of roots; we now fix a set $R^{+}$ of positive roots.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Consider two elements $\mu$ and $\lambda$ of ${\mathfrak {h}}_{0}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] We are mainly interested in the case where $\mu$ and $\lambda$ are integral, but this assumption is not necessary to the definition we are about to introduce.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] We then say that $\mu$ is **higher** than $\lambda$ , which we write as $\mu \succeq \lambda$ , if $\mu -\lambda$ is expressible as a linear combination of positive roots with non-negative real coefficients.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] This means, roughly, that "higher" means in the directions of the positive roots.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] We equivalently say that $\lambda$ is "lower" than $\mu$ , which we write as $\lambda \preceq \mu$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] This is only a *partial* ordering; it can easily happen that $\mu$ is neither higher nor lower than $\lambda$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] An integral element $\lambda$ is *dominant* if $(\lambda ,\gamma )\geq 0$ for each positive root $\gamma$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Equivalently, $\lambda$ is dominant if it is a *non-negative* integer combination of the fundamental weights.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] In the $A_{2}$ case, the dominant integral elements live in a 60-degree sector.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The notion of being dominant is not the same as being higher than zero.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Note the grey area in the picture on the right is a 120-degree sector, strictly containing the 60-degree sector corresponding to the dominant integral elements.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The set of all λ (not necessarily integral) such that $(\lambda ,\gamma )\geq 0$ for all positive roots $\gamma$ is known as the *fundamental Weyl chamber* associated to the given set of positive roots.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] A weight $\lambda$ of a representation V of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is called a **highest weight** if every other weight of V is lower than $\lambda$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] (4) every dominant, algebraically integral element is the highest weight of an irreducible representation.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] The last point is the most difficult one; the representations may be constructed using Verma modules.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] A representation (not necessarily finite dimensional) *V* of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is called *highest-weight module* if it is generated by a weight vector *v* ∈ *V* that is annihilated by the action of all positive root spaces in ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Every irreducible ${\mathfrak {g}}$ -module with a highest weight is necessarily a highest-weight module, but in the infinite-dimensional case, a highest weight module need not be irreducible.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] For each $\lambda \in {\mathfrak {h}}^{*}$ —not necessarily dominant or integral—there exists a unique (up to isomorphism) simple highest-weight ${\mathfrak {g}}$ -module with highest weight λ, which is denoted *L*(λ), but this module is infinite dimensional unless λ is dominant integral.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] It can be shown that each highest weight module with highest weight λ is a quotient of the Verma module *M*(λ).
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] This is just a restatement of *universality property* in the definition of a Verma module.
[src:representation-theory/weight-representation-theory] Every *finite-dimensional* highest weight module is irreducible.
